EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs come up the drive doing about half the speed of the county flatbed truck behind them. They park in a row, doors open together.

Cricket steps off the porch and stands waiting, shoulders back.

ADMINISTRATOR PELL, 50s, lanyard over a zip fleece, gets out reading a folder, and doesn't look at Cricket at all. Behind him, WADE HALVERSEN, county deputy, mid-40s. Cricket taught him to drive a tractor in this yard, twenty years back. Four MOVERS in matching polos follow.

PELL:
Mr. Dawes! There he is. This is a routine action, sir, nothing dramatic. The county's executing on the delinquent assessment — that's their side. I'm only here for the federal paperwork.

CRICKET:
The bank logged my paperwork received next cycle. I have sixty days.

PELL:
That's the bank. The bank isn't the county. And neither one of them is federal. You're dealing with three separate systems today, Mr. Dawes. They don't wait on each other. Nobody's done anything wrong here.

He hands Cricket a pink sheet without stopping his walk to the barn.

INT. DAWES BARN - CONTINUOUS

The movers roll the door wide. Daylight falls across the simulator.

MOVER #1:
What is this thing?

Nobody answers him. Pell circles the rig, checking it against an inventory sheet.

PELL:
Item one. Ex-NASA descent trainer, government property, disposition never finalized. Gyroscopic couch, panels — one altitude indicator—

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell looks at the sheet. Makes a small correction with his pen.

PELL:
Noted.

CRICKET:
It was surplus. Nineteen seventy-five. Told it'd be scrapped otherwise.

PELL:
(not looking up)
Paperwork says otherwise.

He peels a long orange sticker off a backing sheet and lays it across the main panel, smoothing it down with his thumb: LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD — EX-NASA ASSET RECOVERY — EXCLUDED FROM PUBLIC AUCTION.

PELL:
(easy, like he's said it a hundred times)
Whatever trained a man to fly, whatever flew — that's shared heritage now, Mr. Dawes. Not yours specially. Not America's specially. Everybody's.

CRICKET:
(quiet, hard)
Not one of you ever built a thing out here. Now it's all yours.

PELL:
(already moving on)
Everything's compliance now. It's fairer that way. Same rules for everybody.

Pell moves off down the row, checking boxes. Wade lingers a half step behind, hat still in his hand.

WADE:
(low, just to Cricket)
County was gonna auction it, Earl. Might've covered your bill, might not, but it would've been something. Federal list came down Tuesday — anything they can call aerospace, they take it whole, ahead of the county, ahead of everybody. County don't see a dime. Nobody does.

CRICKET:
Where's it go?

WADE:
Warehouse outside Lincoln, is what I hear. Same one as the rest of it.

Cricket looks at him a moment. Nods once, like it's the answer he already had.

The movers unbolt the crew couch. A ratchet slips; a mover barks a knuckle and swears; Cricket hands him the correct socket off the pegboard. The mover takes it and can't look at him.

The Deputy stands near the door with his thumbs in his belt, studying the dirt floor.

Pell reaches the logbook wall. Hundreds of dated spines. He runs his pen light along a shelf, pulls one notebook, flips three pages of grid-ruled block printing.

PELL:
Personal papers.

He drops it back in its slot, crooked.

PELL:
No salvage value. Leave them.

The first dolly rolls toward the door with the crew couch strapped to it. Then it stops.

Cricket is standing in the doorway. Square in it, feet set, hands at his sides.

The mover looks back at Pell. Pell looks at Cricket.

PELL:
Mr. Dawes. This is executed. It's paper now.

Cricket doesn't move. Doesn't say anything either. The barn goes quiet, six men standing around the couch on the dolly.

Pell nods at the Deputy.

The Deputy comes over slow, and stops in front of Cricket, close, hat in his hand.

DEPUTY:
Earl.

CRICKET:
You'll have to move me, Wade.

Wade stands there a moment. Then he puts his hat on, takes Cricket's arm with both hands, gentle, and walks him three steps aside — and Cricket lets him, because it's Wade.

The dolly rolls past. Cricket's eyes never leave the couch, all the way onto the flatbed.

EXT. DAWES FARM - LATER

The simulator rides the flatbed in pieces, chained at four corners.

The movers file past the porch. Peg holds the screen door open for them and nods each one through.

PEG:
Doorframe's fresh painted. Mind it.

The Deputy is last. He hands Cricket the county copy, folded small.

DEPUTY:
There's an appeal window at the courthouse. It's open till four.

CRICKET:
Thank you, Wade.

The Deputy gets in his cruiser. Pell pauses at his SUV door and takes in the farm, the barn, the sky. He nods at each.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But as the Accord reminds us — harmony is a verb.

He gets in. The convoy pulls out, flatbed last. Dust hangs over the drive and settles.

INT. DAWES BARN - DUSK

The barn, half empty. Where the simulator stood: a clean rectangle of dust, bolt holes at the corners.

Cricket stands at its edge, alone a moment first. His hand comes up and presses hard against the back of his neck. One breath. Then his hand drops and his back goes straight again.

Peg comes in and stands next to him. Neither says anything for a while. Straight backs, both of them.

PEG:
Supper's on in twenty.

She goes. Cricket looks at the rectangle one more moment.

Then he crosses to the workbench — they left the radio — pulls the stool in, and keys the mic.

CRICKET:
(into mic)
Net's open. Wednesday.

Static. Then, fast:

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Copy Wednesday.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
About time.

Cricket sets the mic down and reaches up and pulls the work light on.

CUT TO:
